entry.title: Commius elegans
entry.content: Lots on a Cherry Ballart (Exocarpos cupressiformis). I notice there are a few pics on the internet of this species on Exocarpos species. They are adept at hiding, by moving to the other side of the twig/branch they are on.

entry.title: Netelia spp.
entry.content: About half the size of the other common, large red Netelia wasp seen at this location. ID as Netelia spp. by Ken Walker who is also not sure it is Netelia spp.. Ken added "There are several genera (eg: Enicophilus, Ophion, Leptophion, Riekophion etc) that all have the same body shape and colour. The wing venation is the key to distinguishing these genera. I have punted for Netelia as and identification because I believe I can see a small triangular cell on the outer margins of the forewings."

entry.title: Ichneumonidae spp.
entry.content: White 'spectacles'. White socks on rear legs. White bands on antennae. In open woodland. Exhibited hunting wasp behaviour (short low flights, antennae monitoring ground activity). Same species as 12494. Very small.

entry.title: Diamma bicolor
entry.content: Despite the name it is a parasitic wasp. Females are wingless & often seen wandering on the ground looking for mole crickets. They lay an egg on the paralysed cricket, with the cricket then being used as food for the developing wasp larva.

entry.content: On A. mearnsii. Many plants in the area dead or defoliated. Many still healthy too. In this this area A. leprosa var. uninervia is also being seriously damaged or killed (apparently by a very similar but different species).

entry.title: Peltoschema orphana

entry.title: Delta bicinctus
entry.content: Orange Potter Wasp (lives near water, required for pot making). Seems to be distinguished from Delta latreillei latreillei by a three striped abdomen (orange-black-orange, only black-orange in latreillei) and different black & orange pattern on thorax.

entry.title: Cryptocheilus bicolor
entry.content: Spider-hunting wasp with prey. Pulled it along ground and down crack in clay pictured in 2nd photo. They are often seen flying/patrolling just above the ground. ID by Ken Walker.

entry.title: Tiphiidae spp.
entry.content: Female is wingless. Adults feed on nectar. Female burrows into the ground, parasitising beetle larvae & mole crickets. They are important pollinators of native plants. Females sometimes mistaken for ants. (adapted from ABC website)
